@* @ref captures a reference to a rendered element. In Blazor that reference is opaque -- its only
   public surface is FocusAsync(); ElementReference.Id is a framework-internal GUID with no DOM
   meaning, so it is deliberately NOT part of this slice (decision 132).

   The lowering: an element the template names with @ref simply BECOMES that name. Blazor needs an
   ElementReference because it hands the id across the .NET/JS boundary; Filament emits the element
   into a JS const, so @ref="box" only decides what that const is CALLED. FocusAsync() -> .focus().

   DOM contract: #box starts unfocused; clicking #go focuses it, so document.activeElement.id
   becomes "box". That transition IS the measurement (BENCH n°51). *@

<div id="wrap"><input id="box" @ref="box" /><button id="go" @onclick="Focus">go</button></div>

@code {
    private ElementReference box;
    async Task Focus() { await box.FocusAsync(); }
}
